http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Vocal Music I Fine Arts Curriculum Framework

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Vocal Music I is a two-semester course designed to teach students music fundamentals and vocal music techniques. Vocal Music I students are expected to develop beginning performance techniques in solo, small group, and large group settings, with emphasis on reading and performing vocally using appropriate articulation, dynamics, and interpretive skills. Students will critique and reflect on their own performances and the performances of others. Students will perform vocal music in a variety of settings including, but not limited to, concerts, solo and ensemble performances, and festivals. Students will critique and reflect on their own performances and the performances of others. Students will make connections between music traditions and other arts, disciplines, and cultures.
Skills and Techniques
Students shall demonstrate and apply the essential skills and techniques to produce music.

Sing using proper vocal technique
  • breathing and posture
  • free and clear tone, using accurate intonation
  • articulation (e.g., pure vowels, consonant sounds)
  • dynamics and tempi as indicated by markings in the score
Demonstrate independence by performing alone or in an ensemble
Respond to basic conducting gestures
Sing easy literature with and without instrumental accompaniment (e.g., rounds, canons, descants, two-part harmony)
Demonstrate appropriate small and large ensemble performance techniques during formal and/or informal performances (e.g., balance, blend)
Sight-sing simple melodies chosen by the instructor using a consistent method
Sight-sing ensemble parts

Demonstrate through performance an understanding of the language of music
  • basic notation (e.g., staves, clefs, note and rest values, intervals, chords)
  • interpretive notation (e.g., music symbols)
  • simple meter (e.g., , , )
Creative Expression
Students shall demonstrate creative expression through music.

Sing in a manner reflecting the expressive qualities of music in rehearsal and performance including dynamic and tempo markings
  • piano (p)
  • mezzo piano (mp)
  • mezzo forte (mf)
  • forte (f)
  • crescendo
  • decrescendo
  • andante
  • adagio
Improvise call-and-response patterns
Critical Analysis
Students shall listen to, analyze, describe, and evaluate music.
Apply currently taught choral techniques and musicianship in the evaluation of music performances
Evaluate musical performance by comparing them to exemplary models
Connections
Students shall demonstrate and apply knowledge of connections between music and other disciplines.
Exhibit self-discipline and teamwork in daily rehearsals and musical performances
Model appropriate etiquette as both a performer and an observer
Perform music literature from a variety of styles, time periods, and cultures using appropriate interpretation
Identify common elements and descriptive terms used in music with those used in other disciplines
